</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Western European countries and Canada have pledged $1.8 billion in aid over the 
next three years to war-ravaged Central America, provided that the region makes 
progress toward peace and democratic reforms, U.N. officials said. The money is 
to be administered by the U.N. Development Program, which has drawn up a 
program for the region that would cost a total of $4.3 billion. The program, 
known as the Special Plan for Economic Cooperation for Central America, ranges 
from measures to help Central American refugees to steps that would reactivate 
the defunct Central American Common Market, reduce the region's foreign debt 
and promote industry and agriculture. 
