<P>
CURBS ON PLO TALKS SOUGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Senate, under pressure from the Bush Administration, has agreed to postpone 
consideration of a bill that would place new restrictions on Washington's 
dialogue with the Palestine Liberation Organization, the New York Times 
reported. Israeli officials are putting increased pressure on the 
Administration and Congress to stop the meetings, which began after PLO 
Chairman Yasser Arafat stated late last year that the group had renounced 
terrorism and accepted Israel's right to exist. The legislation, sponsored by 
Sens. Jesse Helms (R-N.C.) and John F. Kerry (D-Mass.), would bar U.S.-PLO 
talks unless President Bush certified that participants had no connection to 
acts of terror. The measure is reported to also have bipartisan support in the 
House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
