<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST /LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: EMBEZZLER SENTENCED FOR VIOLATING PROBATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A former fund-raiser for Retinitis Pigmentosa International, who embezzled 
$50,000 from the charity, was sentenced Tuesday to eight months in prison for 
violating his probation by committing another crime. 
</P>
<P>
Van Nuys Superior Court Judge Sherman Juster ordered Daniel Jay Sonners, 28, to 
serve the eight months consecutively with a two-year sentence imposed last 
month for an unrelated burglary. 
</P>
<P>
In December, Juster had sentenced Sonners to four years probation after he 
pleaded guilty to grand theft from the charity. 
</P>
<P>
As part of a plea agreement, Sonners was to repay the Woodland Hills 
organization by Dec. 8, 1989, Deputy Dist. Atty. Michael Pargament said. 
</P>
<P>
Sonners had returned $25,000 of the money, Pargament said, when he was arrested 
Feb. 7 on suspicion of burglarizing a private postal office in Westwood on Jan. 
19 and Jan. 22. He pleaded guilty to one count of burglary of the office. 
</P>
<P>
As a result of Sonners' incarceration, the charity will not be able to recover 
the remaining $25,000, Pargament said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
