<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLICE AWAITING RESULT OF DONNIE MOORE AUTOPSY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY LOU FULTON, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Police today were awaiting autopsy results for former California Angels star 
relief pitcher Donnie Moore, who fatally shot himself in the head after 
seriously wounding his wife during an argument in their Anaheim Hills home. 
</P>
<P>
Tonya Moore, 35, the baseball player's wife, was hospitalized in critical 
condition Tuesday with at least three gunshot wounds to the chest and abdomen; 
her condition today was upgraded to serious, said Donna Donan-Drasner, director 
of public affairs for Kaiser Permanente Medical Center in Anaheim. She remains 
in the hospital's intensive care unit. 
</P>
<P>
The couple's 17-year-old daughter, Demetria, drove her mother to the hospital, 
where she collapsed. A CT scan showed that no bullets 
</P>
<P>
RELATED STORY: Page 8 
</P>
<P>
remain in Tonya Moore's body and no surgery is planned at this time, said 
Randall Johnson, a lawyer and friend of the family who is serving as the 
Moores' spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
"She has been coherent and able to speak with her family," Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
Demetria Moore and her two brothers, 10-year-old Donnie Jr. and 7-year-old 
Ronnie, are staying with friends, Johnson said. Initially, "the two boys were 
doing pretty good," Johnson said, "but they had a sleepless night." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Parents Flying From Texas 
</P>
<P>
Police investigators had no additional information about the shootings this 
morning pending the release of Moore's autopsy results this afternoon, said 
Anaheim Police Lt. Marc Hedgpeth. 
</P>
<P>
The parents of both Tonya and Donnie Moore are flying to Orange County today 
from their homes in Texas, Johnson said. Friends of the family, including 
people from the Angels organization and Demetria's high school classmates, have 
visited the hospital to offer assistance, Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
Funeral arrangements for Donnie Moore, 35, are pending until the Moores' 
parents arrive. 
</P>
<P>
"Right now, everyone is not really sure what to do," Johnson said. "It would be 
easier if we had Tonya to make some decisions." 
</P>
<P>
RELATED STORY: Page 8 
</P>
</TEXT>
